flowRoot.flowPara: Neurons in the primary somatosensory cortex (S1) respond to peripheral
stimulation with synchronised bursts of spikes, which lock to the macroscopic
600 Hz EEG wavelets (hf-EEG).
We fitted unit recordings from macaque monkeys with two phenomenological
models: the spike-train probability model (STPM) and the general linear model
(GLM).
S1-like synchronised bursts of spikes are generated by: 1) high-amplitude synaptic
inputs and 2) absolute and relative refractoriness.
Similar to the experimental data, the trial-to-trial variability in the model can be
decomposed into several stereotyped temporal spike patterns consisting of spikes
and interleaving silences.
Common input fluctuations introduce correlations between the single-neuron spike
patterns and the hf-EEG, as observed experimentally.
The biophysical mechanisms of the S1 spike patterns consist in the combined
feedforward thalamic and intracortical inputs rendering the neuron in a high-
conductance state, where excitation is nearly balanced out by the inhibition.
Neural systems could use refractoriness to encode variable cortical states into
stereotypical short-term spike patterns amenable to processing at neuronal timescales.
